communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Safety National Investigation
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

all records, correspondence, and supporting documentation related to the California Department of Insurance’s Market Conduct Examination of Safety National Casualty Corporation, as adopted April 30, 2025. This includes but is not limited to: (1) the specific claim files reviewed during the examination (redacted as necessary), (2) internal guidelines or claims procedures submitted by the company, (3) examiner workpapers or notes, (4) correspondence between CDI and Safety National regarding findings or corrective actions, and (5) any corrective action plans, compliance reports, or follow-up monitoring related to the violations cited in the report.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Fecteau

communications.subject: RE: PRA-2025-00455 (PY) Req. for All Records, Correspondence, and Supporting Documentation Re. the Market Conduct Examination of Safety National Casualty Corporation (NAIC: 15105, CA: 3605-3)
communications.communication:
Good afternoon, Matthew,

On July 3, 2025, the California Department of Insurance (“Department”) Custodian of Records received your request for information regarding the above-referenced matter, which has been treated as a request pursuant to the California Public Records Act (Gov. Code, § 7920.000 et seq.).

Specifically, your request seeks the following regarding the market conduct exam of Safety National Casualty Corporation (NAIC #: 15105, CA #: 3605-3):


  1.  All records, correspondence, and supporting documentation related to the California Department of Insurance’s Market Conduct Examination of Safety National Casualty Corporation, as adopted April 30, 2025. This includes but is not limited to:
     *   The specific claim files reviewed during the examination (redacted as necessary);
     *   Internal guidelines or claims procedures submitted by the company;
     *   Examiner workpapers or notes;
     *   Correspondence between CDI and Safety National regarding findings or corrective actions; and
     *   Any corrective action plans, compliance reports, or follow-up monitoring related to the violations cited in the report.

After a reasonable search and inquiry, the Department has concluded its search and located responsive records. Please be advised that records pertaining to the specific claim files reviewed during the examination, internal guidelines or claims procedures submitted by the company, examiner workpapers or notes, and correspondence between CDI and the company are confidential and not subject to disclosure under Insurance Code sections 735.5, subdivision (c), and 12919, Evidence Code section 1040, Government Code sections 7927.500, 7929.000, 7922.000, and 7927.705, the official information privilege, and the deliberative process privilege.

Regarding your request #1e, any agreed corrective action plans can be found in the published exam report. Please visit the Department’s public website to access published Market Conduct Exam Reports<https://interactive.web.insurance.ca.gov/apex_extprd/f?p=151:1::::::>.

Sincerely,

David Lopez
Senior Legal Analyst
California Department of Insurance
Legal Branch | Government Law Bureau
300 Capitol Mall, 17th Floor
Sacramento, CA 95814
Office: (916) 492-3115
CA Department of Insurance<https://www.insurance.ca.gov/>

CONFIDENTIALITY NOTICE: This communication with its contents may contain confidential and/or legally privileged information. It is solely for the use of the intended recipient(s). Unauthorized interception, review, use or disclosure is prohibited and may violate applicable laws including the Electronic Communications Privacy Act. If you are not the intended recipient, please contact the sender and destroy all copies of the communication.

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: BPHC Syringe Distribution Data (2018–2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to M.G.L. c. 66, § 10, I request the following records:

Records reflecting the total number of needles or syringes distributed by the Boston Public Health Commission or any BPHC-operated, BPHC-funded, or BPHC-affiliated programs, contractors, or grantees, from January 1, 2018 through December 31, 2024. This includes syringe distribution through:

* AHOPE (Access, Harm Reduction, Overdose Prevention and Education)
* Community Care in Reach (CCiR)
* Public Health Vending Machines
* Mobile health units
* Harm reduction outreach teams
* Any other BPHC-sponsored distribution or syringe access initiatives


Examples of responsive documents may include:

* Annual or monthly summary reports
* Internal BPHC program dashboards or spreadsheets, tracking tools
* Reporting forms from contractors or partners
* Aggregate outreach data (e.g., from AHOPE, CCiR)
* Grant reporting documentation
* Email attachments with syringe count data
* Invoices or procurement logs reflecting distributed quantities
* Internal communications or memos comparing distribution to collection


Background and Justification for Expected Existence of Records

This request is supported by multiple public records and statements issued by the Boston Public Health Commission itself, confirming that syringe distribution is tracked internally:

1. BPHC budget testimony (May 2025): “Over one million syringes \[were] collected… significantly outpacing the number distributed.”
   [https://citizenportal.ai/Search/View?dp=1\&key=3241221-e950d530c6805df2a245d52f98b87f27](https://citizenportal.ai/Search/View?dp=1&key=3241221-e950d530c6805df2a245d52f98b87f27)

2. Community Care in Reach (Frontiers Public Health): “96,601 syringes distributed” by a BPHC-partnered program with weekly reporting by AHOPE staff.
   [https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpubh.2020.00501/full](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpubh.2020.00501/full)

3. AHOPE return rate (Boston 25 News): BPHC data showed a 116% return rate in 2018.
   [https://www.boston25news.com/news/boston-officials-expanding-clean-needle-exchange-programs-across-the-city/994414424/](https://www.boston25news.com/news/boston-officials-expanding-clean-needle-exchange-programs-across-the-city/994414424/)

4. BPHC Peer-Based Syringe Removal RFP (2024): Requires vendors to report syringe pickup through a BPHC data collection system.
   [https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2024/05/Peer-based%20Syringe%20Removal%20Team%20RFP\_0.pdf](https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2024/05/Peer-based%20Syringe%20Removal%20Team%20RFP_0.pdf)

5. BPHC Cabinet Planning Document (2024): States the objective to “collect more syringes than distributed.”
   [https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2024/04/V3%2014-%2025%20A%20Public-Health-Cabinet.pdf](https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2024/04/V3%2014-%2025%20A%20Public-Health-Cabinet.pdf)

6. BPHC Strategic Plan (2019–2022): Requires performance metrics and program data tracking across all BPHC initiatives.
   [https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2021/03/BPHC%20Strategic%20Plan%202019-2022%20%28Final%20for%20Web%29.pdf](https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2021/03/BPHC%20Strategic%20Plan%202019-2022%20%28Final%20for%20Web%29.pdf)

7. WBUR (2015): BPHC reported AHOPE distributed over 150,000 syringes the prior year.
   [https://www.wbur.org/news/2015/06/22/opioid-overdose-ahope-needle-exchange](https://www.wbur.org/news/2015/06/22/opioid-overdose-ahope-needle-exchange)

8. RIZE Program Metrics (LifeSpan Slides): Syringe distribution is an explicit program metric for BPHC-affiliated harm reduction efforts.
   [https://www.lifespan.org/sites/default/files/lifespan-files/documents/centers/rize/psc-meeting\_rize\_final.pdf](https://www.lifespan.org/sites/default/files/lifespan-files/documents/centers/rize/psc-meeting_rize_final.pdf)

9. CDC Grant Requirements: SSP grant reporting includes syringe distribution tracking.
   [https://www.cdc.gov/syringe-services-programs/php/funding/index.html](https://www.cdc.gov/syringe-services-programs/php/funding/index.html)

10. SAMHSA Harm Reduction Grants (ARPA): Require tracking of distributed syringes if funded.
    [https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/harm-reduction](https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/harm-reduction)

11. "AHOPE, the mobile health program’s harm reduction team from the Boston Public Health Commission, on average takes 112 syringes
off the street for every 100 syringes distributed, meaning their syringe exchange program results in fewer needles in circulation" https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2019/01/29/HRC%20Taveras%201-28-2019.pdf

Please confirm receipt and provide an initial response within the statutory period. I am available to clarify or narrow the scope if helpful.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brian McCarter

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All department policy and guidance documents regarding transgender inmates, including but not limited to gender-affirming medical care, housing and treatment by staff. I also request records of any proposed and/or enacted changes to said policies made on or after Nov. 6, 2024 until date of search, if such documents exist.

I request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Ileana Garnand.

communications.subject: Re: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Virginia DOC transgender policies
communications.communication:
Thank you for your request for public records made in accordance with the Virginia Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) (§ 2.2-3700 et seq.). Please be advised that pursuant to § 2.2-3704(A) of the Code of Virginia, “all public records shall be open to citizens of the Commonwealth, representatives of newspapers and magazines with circulation in the Commonwealth, and representatives of radio and television stations broadcasting in or into the Commonwealth during the regular office hours of the custodian of such records...The custodian may require the requester to provide his name and legal address.”

Therefore, unless you are associated with the media, please provide a legal Virginia address to show your residency. Please respond with this information to move forward with your FOIA request. The statutory timeline for the Virginia Department of Correction’s response is tolled until you respond with a legal Virginia address.

Sincerely,

Anne-Cabrié Forsythe
FOIA Officer
(804) 963-2953

title: Organized Retail Crime Task Force: Auror

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Organized Retail Crime Task Force: Auror
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the Organized Retail Crime Theft Task Force announced on June 23, 2022, specifically concerning the implementation, use, and discussion of Auror's crime intelligence platform.

1. All contracts, MOUs, RFPs, or service agreements between the AG's Office and Auror Inc. (auror.co) dated June 23, 2022, to present
1a. Amendments, scope-of-work documents, or SLA agreements related to Auror's services
1b. Invoices, payment receipts, or procurement documents for Auror software/services

2. Budget allocations specific to Auror platform implementation
2a. Documentation of federal/state grants used to fund Auror-related expenditures

3. Training manuals, guides, or protocols for Auror platform use by task force members
3a. Video recordings of Auror software training sessions
3b. Email communications regarding training schedules or materials

4. All incident reports, intelligence briefings, or case files generated through Auror's platform
4a. Spreadsheets/databases tracking organized retail crime incidents processed via Auror
4b. Performance metrics/reports evaluating Auror's effectiveness (2022-2024)

5. Records of technical malfunctions, data inaccuracies, or security breaches involving Auror
5a. Formal complaints from task force members or partner agencies about Auror's system
5b. Internal audits or third-party assessments of Auror's compliance with state data laws

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Federal government Rule 11 letters (Securities and Exchange Commission)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. In any litigation before a federal district court on behalf of the United States or any agency, department, official, or employee thereof, any letter sent by your attorneys containing any of the following terms: 
a. "Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11"
b. "Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, Rule 11"
c. "FRCP 11"
d. "Fed. R. Civ. P. 11"
e. "Fed. R. Civ. P., Rule 11"

2. Any policies, manuals, or guidance (not including guidance specific to a particular case) concerning pursuit of Rule 11 sanctions.

This request is limited to correspondence sent (or policies, manuals, or guidance utilized) on or after January 1, 2020.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

title: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Thirteenth Judicial District

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Thirteenth Judicial District
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.

- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Bowling

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Thirteenth Judicial District
communications.communication:
-----BY EMAIL ONLY-----

To:          Mr. Joshua Bowling
MuckRock News
              189420-25968973@requests.muckrock.com

Fr:          Melissa Howden
                Records Custodian 13th Judicial District Attorney of New Mexico

Re:         IPRA Request re Brady Giglio

Dear Mr. Bowling,

I, the undersigned am the Records Custodian for the 13th Judicial District Attorney of New Mexico. I received your request forwarded to me on 7/10/2025 for:


- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.

- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.


The 13th Judicial District does not maintain any lists, datasets or spread sheets detailing potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States. During the current administration of District Attorney Barbara Romo, we have had one Giglio disclosure letter and case re: former Officer Robert Turney in our Cibola County District. Included here is a document fragment detailing the underlying case. The allegation of misconduct came from a discovery from the district court; therefore, we don’t have specific additional records other than the attached letters to:

  *   The letter the Sheriff of Cibola County asked our deputy to draft and send.
  *   The spreadsheet detailing the cases for which we had to submit a disclosure letter.
  *   A copy of the disclosure letter.( Each letter heading was corrected for each case otherwise the body of the letter was the same, the letter attached is a sample).
  *   Letter to the Defense Counsel
Sincerely,


//Melissa Howden//


Melissa A. Howden
Chief Administrative Officer
13th Judicial District Attorney of New Mexico
711 Camino del Pueblo Sur
Post Office Box 1750
Bernalillo, NM 87004
505-771-7439 Office
505-269-4915 Mobile

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request - Sebastian
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Dear Sebastian Police Department,


I am writing to formally request access to video footage from a police intervention, specifically from the body camera worn by the officer(s) and the dashcam of the police vehicles involved. Article:

https://www.sebastiandaily.com/crime/sebastian-woman-45-arrested-for-dui-kicking-cops-53901/



Exact address of incident: Sebastian Boulevard (CR-512)

Exact date of incident: 7th of August, 2023 around 11 p.m

Names of parties involved: Jennifer Brown



I intend to use this footage solely for educational purposes to promote a better understanding of law enforcement procedures and the application of the law.


I understand that there may be associated costs for providing this footage, and I am more than willing to cover any fees incurred. Please inform me about the necessary procedures and the costs involved.


Thank you in advance for your assistance. I trust that this footage will be invaluable for my educational efforts, and I greatly appreciate your cooperation.



Best regards,

George Smith

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

George Smith

If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 106 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 785 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,695 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,088 days for processing.

Respectfully,


Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
F: (540) 868-4391
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: Sex Offender Registry and Information on Community Supervision

communications.subject: The Kansas Open Records Act Request: Sex Offender Registry and Information on Community Supervision
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Kansas Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

The exact number of people who are 

1) on both the sex offender registry and probation; and
2) on both the sex offender registry and parole;

as per the latest available data is requested.

If this cannot be provided, I request records that include:

The list of people on probation
The list of people on parole
The list of people on the sex offender registry

as per the latest available data. 

If this data is held by another agency, I request the name of that agency.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Wendy Sawyer

title: Oklahoma Open Records Request – February 10, 2025 High-Speed Pursuit and Arrest of Tyreese Ford

communications.subject: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request: Oklahoma Open Records Request – February 10, 2025 High-Speed Pursuit and Arrest of Tyreese Ford
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Oklahoma Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

copies of all video and audio records related to the pursuit, crash, and arrest of Tyreese Ford on February 10, 2025, by the Oklahoma County Sheriff’s Office.

Please include:

All body-worn camera footage from deputies involved in the arrest

All dashcam/in-car video from vehicles involved in the pursuit

Helicopter or aerial footage, if applicable

911 calls, dispatch recordings, or radio traffic related to the pursuit and crash response

Footage capturing the Taser deployment and arrest at the crash site

Any available photos or video of the crash aftermath, including the damaged white car and pickup

Incident Details:

Date & Time: February 10, 2025

Suspect: Tyreese Ford

Location: Pursuit ended near SW 29th and Council Rd, Oklahoma City, OK

Chase Length: ~7 miles, reaching speeds up to 90 MPH

Events:

Ford fled with a female passenger

Sideswiped a vehicle during the pursuit

Crashed into a pickup at the intersection

Was tased and arrested on scene

Passenger was helped out of the car; airbags deployed

Ford had two active felony warrants related to burglaries

Please inform me of any applicable fees before processing. If any part of the requested records is withheld, I request that you release all non-exempt portions and cite the specific statutory exemptions relied upon.

Thank you for your assistance.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

I received your email that states that your payment is being processed and mailed. However, the address you listed is for the Oklahoma County Detention Center and not the Oklahoma County Sheriff’s Office.
Please do not send your payment to 201 N Shartel Oklahoma City, as we are not associated the detention center.
Please see my previous email which has our agency’s mailing address.
Please call me if you have any questions.
Thank you!

Debi Shaw
Specialist
Criminal Investigations Division
Oklahoma County Sheriff's Office
2101 Northeast 36th Street
Oklahoma City, OK  73111​

Hello, 

Thank you for the info about the correct address! Apologies for the confusion.

We'll go ahead and process a replacement check for the same amount to be sent to 2101 Northeast 36th Street. We kindly ask that you/the detention center return or void the check sent to 201 N Shartel Ave upon receipt. 

Thank you for your continued help with this request.

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Holocaust Survey (Connetquot Central School District)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

By way of background, on August 10, 2022, Governor Kathy Hochul signed into law Chapter 490 of the Laws of 2022 requiring a survey regarding instruction on the Holocaust within New York State public school districts. Through the survey, superintendents are required to attest that the district is teaching about the Holocaust appropriately as part of classroom instruction aligned with the NYS Social Studies Learning Standards and §801 of Education Law.

In October 2022, Deputy Commissioner Angelique Johnson-Dingle sent a memo to public school superintendents including a copy of that survey and instructions for accessing and submitting the survey via the SED Monitoring and Vendor Performance System in the NYSED Business Portal.

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request all of the Holocaust Instruction Survey responses submitted since August 10, 2022.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

title: Request for Body-Worn Camera Footage and Dispatch Logs – Craig & Brian Braunschweig – December 28–29, 2023

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Request for Body-Worn Camera Footage and Dispatch Logs – Craig & Brian Braunschweig – December 28–29, 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Request for all body-worn camera, dash cam footage, and dispatch logs related to Craig and Brian Braunschweig during incidents on December 28–29, 2023 at 7791 Shadyglade Ln, San Diego.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brian Braunschweig

I'm reaching out because this school was recently included on a list of 60 schools that received letters from the Dept. of Education saying they were under investigation for "Antisemitic Discrimination and Harassment."
Source: https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-educations-office-civil-rights-sends-letters-60-universities-under-investigation-antisemitic-discrimination-and-harassment
Also, recently, two students and counting from Columbia University (which is on this list) have been arrested by immigration authorities.
Source: https://apnews.com/article/columbia-university-mahmoud-khalil-ice-arrests-3a8db6e646b786a721089a6f0bc8d9fc

Therefore, pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records (from January 20, 2025 to the time that this request is processed):
1) Any emails between members of your institution's police department/safety office and anyone with the email domain "@ice.dhs.gov" or "@whitehouse.gov" or "@dhs.gov"
2) Any emails between members of your institution's office of the president and anyone with the email domain "@ice.dhs.gov" or "@whitehouse.gov" or "@dhs.gov"
3) Any emails between members of your institution's department of student housing/on-campus living and anyone with the email domain "@ice.dhs.gov" or "@whitehouse.gov" or "@dhs.gov"

I am a reporter for WIRED filing this request in pursuit of a time-sensitive news story; therefore, I ask that my request is expedited.  Also, as a reporter for WIRED, the requested documents are in the public interest and not being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I ask that all fees are waived in the processing of my request. 

When completing this request, please prioritize whichever records would take the least amount of time to be located and released.  Also, I would like these records in electronic format, sent via email or other digital method. Also, if you determine that any of the information qualifies for an exemption from disclosure, I ask you to note whether the exemption is discretionary, and if so, whether it is necessary in this case to exercise your discretion to withhold the information. In any event, please provide a signed notification citing the legal authorities on which you rely if you determine that any of the information is exempt and will not be disclosed.

If there are any questions about my request, or I can provide any clarification that will help expedite the processing of my request, please contact me here. I am also happy to hop on the phone. Thanks again, and I look forward to your reply within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires, as the statute requires, and even sooner if possible.

Best,
Caroline Haskins

title: FOIA Request - Fayette County Opioid Settlement Funds

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Request - Fayette County Opioid Settlement Funds
communications.communication:
Ruth Lanier, County Administrator 
Fayette County Commission
100 N Court Street 
Fayetteville, WV 25840

Dear Ruth Lanier, 

Pursuant to the state open records law W.Va. Code Secs. 29B-1-1 to 29B-1-7, I write to request access to public records regarding Fayette County’s opioid settlement funds. Specifically, I am requesting copies of: 
the amount of funds Fayette County has received so far
the application to apply for funding
the individuals who will review the funding applications
the process by which funds will be awarded
documents or other information detailing how the opioid settlement funds distributed to Fayette County have been awarded through March 1, 2025, if at all, including budgets, grant allocations, and expenditure reports.
any existing or proposed plans outlining future use of said opioid settlement funds, including strategic plans, meeting minutes in which county-level officials participated, and correspondence and attachments regarding funding allocations.
any public reports, audits, or documentation created by the county regarding the accountability and impact of these funds
All attachments, addendums, appendices, exhibits, and other related documents that were included as part of the contracts.

If your agency does not maintain these public records, please let me know who does and include the proper custodian's name and address.
As provided by the open records law, I will expect your response within five (5) working days. See W. Va. Code Sec. 29B-1-3(d).
If you choose to deny this request, please provide a written explanation for the denial including a reference to the specific statutory exemption(s) upon which you rely. Also, please provide all segregable portions of otherwise exempt material.
I would note that willful violation of the open records law is a misdemeanor, punishable by a fine of not less than $200 nor more than $1,000, or imprisonment in the county jail for twenty (20) days, or both. See W. Va. Code Sec. 29B-1-6. Court costs and attorney fees may also be awarded. See Sec. 29B-1-7.
Thank you for your assistance.
Thank you for considering my request.

Sincerely,
Aidan Cornue
(312) 458-5125
amc00069@mix.wvu.edu

title: Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Request: Body-Worn Camera Footage - Arrest of Matthew Leibach (February  14, 2023)

communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Request: Body-Worn Camera Footage - Arrest of Matthew Leibach (February  14, 2023)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to Chapter 610 of the Missouri Revised Statutes, also known as the Missouri Sunshine Law, primarily deals with the public's right to access information from public governmental bodies in Missouri.

I respectfully request copies of all body-worn camera (BWC) footage related to the arrest of Matthew Leibach on or about February  14, 2023 at approximately 4:48 AM, by the St. Louis County Police.

Specifically, I am requesting:
All body-worn camera footage recorded by any St. Louis County Police Department personnel during the detention, investigation, or arrest of Matthew Leibach also footage of the vehicle chase that resulted in Matthew Leibach crashing the vehicle at Ohio Avenue and Broadway Street in St. Louis City.

Please include footage captured shortly before, during, and immediately after the incident

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brandon Martin

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Division of Corrections)

communications.subject: West Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Division of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the West Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: RE: West Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Division of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern: 

Thank you for your response regarding my records request.

I understand that certain employment-related records may be exempt from disclosure under W. Va. Code §29B-1-4(a)(2), and I appreciate you taking the time to review the request.

If possible, I’d like to ask whether there is a staff member within the Division of Corrections and Rehabilitation responsible for overseeing or coordinating mental health programming across West Virginia facilities. I am not requesting confidential personnel records — only the name and work contact information of a relevant point of contact.

We are reaching out regarding a free, volunteer-led meditation program designed to support emotional regulation and well-being for incarcerated individuals, and would be grateful for any guidance on whom to contact to explore this offering further.

Thank you again for your time and consideration.

Warm regards,
Andrew Ma

communications.subject: Iowa Open Records Law Request: SOR and Community Supervision
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Iowa Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am seeking data to understand offenders who have double forms of community supervision (i.e. parole and sex offender registry (SOR)). Iowa Department of Corrections had helped to provide a list of all offenders on probation and parole. I would like to be able to cross reference that list with the current Iowa SOR to pull the data I am seeking. I would like to request that the Division provide the list of offenders on the SOR currently. 

If that request is not possible, I wonder if the Division has: the exact number of people who are 1) on both the sex offender registry and probation; and 2) on both the sex offender registry and parole; as per the latest available data is requested.

If another agency has this data, I request the name of that agency.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Wendy Sawyer

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-00644-F
communications.communication:
Dear Director at the Office of Information Policy, 

This letter is in reference to FOIA Request #24-00644-F which you closed on March 25th 2024 after a lengthy response suggesting no responsive documents have met the plain letter language of my FOIA request. I believe this request was closed in error and am humbly appealing your judgement. 

1) In denying this request your office suggested that the request for correspondences was too broad. However, your response does not indicate that an actual search has occurred. In order to help your team limit your search I am rewriting this search to better help guide your search. I am also available for a call if you would like to discuss further refining this search. 

- Emails, letters, and text messages between the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) and India’s Directorate of Revenue Intelligence (DRI), and the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), Customs and Border Protection (CBP), Homeland Security Investigations (HSI) and US Postal Inspection Service (USPIS) mentioning "Operation Broader Sword" between January 1st 2022 and the date this request is full-filled.

I believe this request both specifies types of correspondences, the senders and receivers, and the specific date ranges for which you to search. Operation Broader Sword is a highly publicized operation. (See: https://in.usembassy.gov/u-s-and-india-cooperate-on-operation-broader-sword-to-stop-international-shipments-of-illegal-and-dangerous-drugs-medical-devices/). The DEA's involvement alongside the other agencies has also been highly publicized. (SEE: https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/us-india-joint-operation-seizes-500-shipments-of-illicit-prescription-drugs-and-medical-devices/article67053528.ece). 

Emails, Text Messages, and Letters sent by public servants in their capacity as public servants are public records. Thus they are FOIA'ble. Retrieving already existing emails, text messages, or letters, is not requesting a new record be created. It is not tantamount to research. 

2) The seizure of 500 shipments of contraband has been highly publicized. (SEE: https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/us-india-joint-operation-seizes-500-shipments-of-illicit-prescription-drugs-and-medical-devices/article67053528.ece). DEA rules mandate such records be kept for at least two years (SEE: https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/mtgs/researcher_train/conf_2019/feb_2019/barron.pdf). 

For this reason, I believe there are in fact responsive documents to the following request:

Any documents including but not limited to seizure records, arrest records, contracts, reports, intelligence briefings regarding "Operation Broader Sword" between January 1st 2022 and the date this request is full-filled.

A reminder that I am a journalist and this information is being requested in the public interest to shed light on the cross-border illicit drug trade impacting US citizens. It is in the public's interest to know about the inflows of such material into the country and therefore I am requesting a waiver of fees. 

Lastly, the FOIA does not require agencies to create new records or to conduct research, analyze data, or answer questions when responding to requests. The retrieval of already existing documents is not research. It is the FOIA officers job to find responsive public documents to a request or provide specific statute exemptions for why a FOIA request hasn't been completed. This has not happened in this case. 

Considering the myriad of media reports about this operation, I believe responsive documents do in fact exist. Please provide a timeline in which you can conduct a reasonable search for these documents. 

Thank you for your time. I am available on the following phone number if you'd like to chat more +1 347 770 4163 / +1 347 775 7522.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Julia Rock

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee

title: $10,000,000  HUD Grant to AIDS Healthcare Foundation for Tenant Education Outreach Program under Blueprint for Renters

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: $10,000,000  HUD Grant to AIDS Healthcare Foundation for Tenant Education Outreach Program under Blueprint for Renters
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1-All  communications, applications, certifications, and representations of the AIDS Healthcare Foundation ("AHF") in obtaining a $10,000,00 grant for HUD's Tenant Education Outreach Program ("TEO").
2. All terms of any agreement that AHF must follow in order to obtain this grant.
3. All terms of any agreement that AHF must in distribution of grant money.
4. Any terms of commitment that AHF signed and/or agreed to, in providing decent, safe, sanitary, healthy, housing for tenants, and/or in providing tenants rights advocates access to the distribution of tenants' rights information. 
5. Any emails between HUD and AHF concerning the TEO program.
6. All disclosures made from AHF concerning or relating to any of the lawsuits against AHF including but not limited to any of the following lawsuits:
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. Karla Leiva, LASC Case No. 22STRO00633, which was in front of Commissioner Laura Cohen who granted the tenant's rights advocate's Anti-SLAPP motion. Ms. Leiva was a tenants’ rights advocate and AHF filed a temporary restraining order against Ms. Leiva, prohibiting her from coming onto AHF properties. Subsequently, Judge Michael R. Powell entered judgment in favor of the tenants' rights advocate on AHF’s remaining claim that our client threw feces at an AHF employee. AHF was ordered to pay the tenants' rights advocate more than $44,000 in attorneys’ fees.
•	Tammy Davis v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, LASC Case No. 20STCV08627, which was in front of Judge Daniel Buckley (Ret.) and now Judge William Highberger. This ongoing case concerns the Madison Hotel’s uninhabitable living conditions. The class has been certified and consists of approximately 350 tenants. This is the case that recently settled this past weekend for $575,000 to tenants, plus nonmonetary relief. Plus AHF's cross-complaint against the City of Los Angeles which was dismissed on the City's Motion for Summary Judgment.
•	Carlos Brum v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, LASC Case No. 23STCV07822, in front of Judge Kenneth Freeman. This ongoing putative class action case concerning the Baltimore Hotel’s uninhabitable living conditions.
•	Alisha Lucero v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, et al., LASC Case No. 19STCV28098. This matter has been resolved, and was in front of Judge Dennis Landin (Ret.) and then Judge Upinder Kalra. This case concerned AHF’s unlawful eviction of Ms. Lucero and throwing away all of her possessions without notice. 
•	Grace Antisdel, William Berry, Julia Bigboy, Linda Carrasco, Dwane Davis, Michael Davis, Enrique Deliz, Tammy Davis, Rodney Duck, Errol Ennis, Edwin Linwood, Kenneth Montgomery, Darnell Moses, Kenneth Owens, Brenda Phillips, Vance Pitts, and Trimal Williams v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, LASC Case No. 21STCV04049. This matter has been resolved and was in front of Judge Stephanie Bowick. The publicly known settlement amount is $820,000, and concerned the Madison’s elevator outages and the effect of those outages on tenants with disabilities.  Plus AHF's cross complaint against the City of Los Angeles, for which the City paid AHF $100,000 to resolve that cross-complaint.
•	James Ellis v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, LASC Case No. 22STCV35702. This matter was recently resolved. The case was in front of Judge Anne Hwang. This case concerned a Madison tenant who had a long history of violent behavior shooting another tenant, James Ellis, and AHF’s failure to evict the violent tenant before the shooting. AHF cross-complained against the County of Los Angeles and the Los Angeles Sheriff’s Department. Judge Hwang sustained the County entities’ demurrer without leave to amend.
•	Annette Turner and Tammy Davis v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, et al., LASC Case No. 20STCV4667. This case is active and is in front of Judge Robert Broadbelt. This case concerns a sexual assault committed by AHF’s unlicensed and unvetted contractor to do repairs in Ms. Davis’s room. This case is also concerning Ms. Turner’s individual uninhabitability claims in her personal unit due to repeated flooding from the common areas.
•	Pernell Monger v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation, LASC Case No. 23STCV19686. This matter is active and in front of Judge Randolph M. Hammock. This concerns a Madison tenant’s personal claims for disability discrimination, failure to accommodate, bedbugs, roaches, and other uninhabitable conditions.
•	Maria Umana, Douglas Umana Gomez, Sasha Salgado, Ruben Flores, Reina Melchor, and Miguel Valencia v. AIDS Healthcare Foundation et al., LASC Case No. 22STCV00361. This case concerns the lack of habitability of AHF’s Sinclair apartment complex. 
The at least 85 evictions AHF has filed against its tenants. The approximate 80 small claims lawsuits AHF has filed against its tenants.
•	•	Michael Weinstein v. City of Los Angeles et al., LASC Case No. BC210058.
•	Michael Weinstein v. City of Los Angeles et al., LASC Case No. BC214564.
•	Michael Weinstein v. City of Los Angeles et al., LASC Case No. BC140892.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. BS161771.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. BC717911.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 19STCP00520.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 19STCP03103.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 19STCP04094.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 19STCP04589.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 19STCP04532.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 20STCV29238. (AHF appealed Judge Rupert Byrdsong sustaining of the City’s demurrer without leave to amend. AHF appealed, and the Appellate court affirmed the dismissal.) 
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 21STCP00049.
•	AIDS Healthcare Foundation v. City of Los Angeles, LASC Case No. 21STCP04176. (Here, AHF sued the City to prevent the development of affordable housing.)


7. Any discussion or disclosure to HUD, or research conducted by HUD, into AHF's involvement with any of the following issues covered in the below news articles:

•	https://www.latimes.com/homeless-housing/story/2020-03-08/homeless-housing-aids-healthcare-foundation-lawsuit-skid-row-tenants
•	https://www.latimes.com/homeless-housing/story/2023-01-20/ahf-madison-hotel-elevator-lawsuit-story
•	https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-02-10/residents-of-a-downtown-hotel-settle-with-aids-healthcare-foundation-over-elevator-failures
•	https://knock-la.com/aids-healthcare-foundation-housing-hazards-1/
•	https://knock-la.com/aids-healthcare-foundation-housing-hazards-2/
•	https://knock-la.com/aids-healthcare-foundation-housing-hazards-3/ 
•	https://www.latimes.com/homeless-housing/story/2024-03-27/aids-healthcare-foundation-acquire-skid-row-housing-trust-portfolio 
•	https://laist.com/news/housing-homelessness/los-angeles-aids-healthcare-foundation-michael-weinstein-madison-hotel-settlement-rent-control-proposition-prop-33

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Annette Morasch

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication:
Re: Case No. 24-FI-HQ-03356

What is the status of this request? It has now been over 30 days with nothing but an autoresponse which assigned the FOIA number.
Thank you.

communications.subject: Request Note Notification Email - U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
communications.communication: "We are currently processing your request and will notify you as soon as the search has been completed. If you have any questions, you may contact me at Robin.L.Berry-Crawford@hud.gov. Thank you"

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication:
It is well past 30 days and it is apparent a writ of mandate will need to be filed against HUD for its failure to follow the public records act requirements. 

Production of communications on a rolling basis is acceptable, but the actual grant and AHF’s signature agreeing to take certain actions —those must be produced immediately.  There is no excuse for what the contract itself cannot be immediately produced.  This issue has been in the LA Times. So produce the contract immediately in order to prevent a writ of mandate being filed against HUD. 

Thank you so much.

communications.subject: Request Note Notification Email - U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
communications.communication: "I apologize for the delay in the processing of your request. In processing these requests, we are responsible for tasking other program offices for the records. The search for your records is near completion. We will keep you informed as your case progresses. If you have additional questions, you may reach me at Robin.L.Berry-Crawford@hud.gov.  Thank you"

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication: I have received your auto-response.  I have called and emailed you personally to learn why it is taking so long to produce an agreement that accompanies handing $10,000,000 to a company.  There is at least an agreement that you can produce now for the public to see. Please produce at least the contract which disburses a significant amount of taxpayer money to an entity that had an injunction entered against it for interfering with tenants’ rights advocates, and is refusing to acknowledge a tenants union.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication: Four months with no response. Why isn't HUD complying with the law?

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication:
United States Representative Laura Friedman's office has contacted you and you have not returned their communication.
I have contacted you repeatedly.
This is a simple request. Why is the contract not even being produced in the interim of HUD looking into other requests?

communications.subject: Request Note Notification Email - U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
communications.communication: "I am working on your case now. "

communications.subject: Request Note Notification Email - U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
communications.communication: "There was an issue with me messages from PAL. I want to inform you that I am working on your case now. I had to get some clarifications from the program office but that has been done. "

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-FI-HQ-03356
communications.communication: Hello, three days ago you stated "I am working on your case now."  And I have not heard anything else.  I am begging you to please just provide the contract and application today and you can roll out the rest of the requested documents later.  It's been five months and you haven't even given me a contract for $10m in federal tax payer money. I fail to see how this is possible.

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: ICT List: September 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Supply records sufficient to show a listing of incident reports (ICT Record List) from September 1, 2023 - September 30, 2023 for all CPS schools.

This request is made on behalf of The FOIA Bakery. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Miriam Bhimani

communications.subject: FOIA Request :: N017815-062525

Dear Miriam :

Miriam Bhimani

Chicago Public Schools (CPS) responds to all public records requests in accordance with the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 5 ILCS 140/1 et seq. 
Due to the volume and complexity of requests received in the normal course of business, CPS is extending the time for its initial response to your request by an additional 5 business days (to 10 business days total beginning on the first business day following receipt of the request) pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/3(e)(v) which allows for the examination and evaluation of the requested records by personnel to determine if they are exempt from disclosure under Section 7 of Illinois FOIA or should be revealed only with appropriate deletions. 
Upon the completion of a response, CPS will provide the first 50 pages to you at no charge.  If a response is more than 50 pages, a fee of 15¢ per page will be charged for each additional page. All applicable fees must be paid prior to the copying. CPS will inform you of any fees due if your paper response exceeds 50 pages. You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you’ll receive an email when your request has been completed. Thank you for using the CPS FOIA Center. 

Track the issue status and respond at: https://cps.mycusthelp.com/WEBAPP//_rs/RequestEdit.aspx?rid=17815

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-public-schools-3121%252Fict-list-september-2023-188443%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAATZ164Jy60iQjs6iHTUOyYGcc%3A1uUdPt%3AOHnHW0QIKT1BUODZkcOQE1YaoQRR5YQKxT2quIV8M1Q 
RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please be advised that certain event reasons have been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c) exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy... “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

communications.communication:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Mission documentation of each sUAS deployment in 2024-2025 so far, sufficient to determine the date, time, location, and purpose of each deployment. Please see P135695-041424, a similar request, for reference.

If this is not available, an index with file name, date created, location (if available), length, and any other available metadata of video files created as a result of sUAS deployments in 2023.

communications.subject: Public Records Request :: P154140-032625
communications.communication:
Thank you for your interest in obtaining public records held by the King County Sheriff’s Office. Your request has been received and is being processed. Your request was received in this office on March 26, 2025 and given the reference number P154140-032625 for tracking purposes. 
 
Within five (5) business days (excluding holidays) after receiving your request, we will: 
 
 
  * Provide the record(s); 
  * Or Acknowledge your request and give you a reasonable estimate of how long it will take to respond; 
  * Or Deny the request in writing, stating the reasons for the denial (this could also include a denial of part of your request and a granting of the remainder). 
The day the request is received does not count as one of the five (5) days. Weekends and holidays observed by the agency are also excluded in the calculation. 
 
Record(s) Requested: To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

title: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University Of Texas At Permian Basin)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas universities: Past and planned student events (University Of Texas At Permian Basin)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

This is a survey of events planned or proposed by recognized or registered student organizations (or individual students or faculty members). I am seeking copies of calendar entries for events that were held or proposed. I am not seeking a search of records held by students or student organizations. I am only seeking information held by the university administration (for example, in an Event Management System, which may be helpful in providing a list of past events and proposed future events). 

If this request is unclear or if I could clarify it in any way, please don't hesitate to ask.

I request:

1. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member during the final two weeks of each term during 2023, 2024, and Winter/Spring 2025. If your institution's academic calendar does not identify a final date of a given term, please use the final day of exams for the term as the final day of the term.

2. All calendar entries (or Event Management System database entries) for events held or sponsored by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m., between January 31, 2023 and July 1, 2025.

3. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be held after 10:00 p.m. and/or before 8:00 a.m. This request is limited to events that are proposed to be held between July 1, 2025 and July 1, 2026. 

4. All calendar entries for events which are or were proposed to be held by a registered student organization, individual student, or faculty member, where the event is proposed to be during the final two weeks of a term in the Fall 2025, Winter 2025-2026, or Spring 2026 semesters/terms. Please us the same means of calculating "final two weeks" as in (1), above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Safety National Complaints (Division of Insurance)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting access to all records in your possession from January 1, 2014, through the present concerning complaints, investigations, or regulatory actions involving Safety National Casualty Corporation, including any affiliated entities such as Safety Specialty Insurance Company and Sedgwick Claims Management Services, Inc. 

Specifically, I request copies of all consumer complaints alleging claim denials, delays, bad faith practices, misrepresentation of coverage, or failure to defend or indemnify insureds; any related correspondence or internal assessments; all regulatory enforcement actions, including market conduct examinations, administrative penalties, consent orders, fines, stipulations, or notices of violation; and any internal memoranda, emails, audit findings, or documentation regarding systemic or repeated misconduct. I also seek any statistical reports, dashboards, or complaint trend summaries reflecting activity related to Safety National during this period.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Fecteau

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Brezhvis
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

File 105-HQ-86659, captioned "Brezhvis" and possibly also "Visit of Soviet Premier Leonid Ilyich Brezhnev to the United States, June 18-26, 1973".

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

title: Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the historical study Office of Personnel: The Position Management and Compensation Division, 1946-1967.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the government and its activities, with some reaching over 100,000 readers in outlets such as MuckRock, Motherboard, Property of the People, AND Magazine, Unicorn Riot, and more. As such, as I have a reasonable expectation of publication and my editorial and writing skills are well established. In addition, I discuss and comment on the files online and make them available through non-profits such as the library Internet Archive and and the journalist non-profit, MuckRock, disseminating them to a large audience. While my research is not limited to this, a great deal of it, including this, focuses on the activities and attitudes of the government itself. As such, it is not necessary for me to demonstrate the relevance of this particular subject in advance.

Additionally, case law states that “proof of the ability to disseminate the released information to a broad cross- section of the public is not required.” Judicial Watch, Inc. v. Dep’t of Justice, 365 F.3d 1108, 1126 (D.C. Cir. 2004); see Carney v. U.S. Dep’t of Justice, 19 F.3d 807, 814-15 (2d Cir. 1994). Further, courts have held that "qualified because it also had “firm” plans to “publish a number of . . . ‘document sets’” concerning United States foreign and national security policy." Under this criteria, as well, I qualify as a member of the news media.

Additionally, courts have held that the news media status "focuses on the nature of the requester, not its request. The provision requires that the request be “made by” a representative of the news media. Id. § 552(a)(4)(A)(ii)(II). A newspaper reporter, for example, is a representative of the news media regardless of how much interest there is in the story for which he or she is requesting information." As such, the details of the request itself are moot for the purposes of determining the appropriate fee category.

As my primary purpose is to inform about government activities by reporting on it and making the raw data available, I request that fees be waived.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

Kimberly Shainfeld
